<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>14532</anchor> <rss>jms-00E7.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00E7</addr>  <route>jms-00E7.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>10</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Transformations of homomorphisms of natural models</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>M</tex> and <tex>N</tex> be <link href="jms-00E4.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic description of natural models">natural models</link>, as depicted schematically below:</p>      <center><img src="resources/42be5cde2f7958382cc0cb155cf2dcd0-web.svg"/></center>  <p>  Let <tex>{ M } \xrightarrow {{ \Phi , \Psi }}{ N }</tex> be two <link href="jms-00E5.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphisms of natural models">(lax) homomorphisms</link> from <tex>M</tex> to <tex>N</tex>. A <em>transformation</em> <tex>{ \Phi } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha }}{ \Psi }</tex> of <link href="jms-00E5.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphisms of natural models">homomorphisms</link> from <tex>M</tex> to <tex>N</tex> is by three cells
  
        <center><img src="resources/7dd9dfb0813a3cdcd54dcdd94a12612d-web.svg"/></center>    such that commute with the components of <tex>\Phi</tex> and <tex>\Psi</tex> in the following sense:
        <center><img src="resources/6a8e4909ef846eb4df254a7de8ba93bf-web.svg"/></center>          <center><img src="resources/c9b75de31052029b90a08ee70930d649-web.svg"/></center>    
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>14533</anchor> <rss>jms-00E6.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00E6</addr>  <route>jms-00E6.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>10</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic description of the bicategory of natural models</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>14534</anchor> <rss>jms-00E4.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00E4</addr>  <route>jms-00E4.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>10</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic description of natural models</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <em>natural model</em> is described by the following structure in the bicategory of (small) categories:</p><ol>  <li>    a sequence of discrete fibrations <tex>E \xrightarrow {p} U \xrightarrow {c}  \mathcal {C}</tex> such that <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> has a terminal object:
          <center><img src="resources/6ad3e14ea5c76eab497ab6118f91c0c7-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  <li>    such that <tex>{ E } \xrightarrow {{ p }}{ U }</tex> has a right adjoint <tex>{ U } \xrightarrow {{ q }}{ E }</tex>:
          <center><img src="resources/5397e4b379397f8db3374766f8469585-web.svg"/></center>            <center><img src="resources/24d758c6e0dc6ce7b98209ebd7f2ca72-web.svg"/></center>            <center><img src="resources/95e89255cd2947fa97349942a93a92bf-web.svg"/></center>    </li></ol></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>14535</anchor> <rss>jms-00E5.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00E5</addr>  <route>jms-00E5.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>10</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphisms of <link href="jms-00E4.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic description of natural models">natural models</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>M</tex> and <tex>N</tex> be <link href="jms-00E4.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic description of natural models">natural models</link>, as depicted schematically below:</p>      <center><img src="resources/42be5cde2f7958382cc0cb155cf2dcd0-web.svg"/></center>  <p>A <em>lax homomorphism</em> <tex>{ M } \xrightarrow {{ \Phi }}{ N }</tex> of <link href="jms-00E4.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic description of natural models">natural models</link> is given by the following data:</p>      <center><img src="resources/900ac81538ffba771b9f39f4a8459ac3-web.svg"/></center>        <center><img src="resources/6e50e6cc0d3ea8a11d027d6f1473830b-web.svg"/></center>  <p>A lax homomorphism <tex>{ M } \xrightarrow {{ \Phi }}{ N }</tex> is called <em>strong</em> when <tex>\Phi _{ \mathcal {C}}</tex> preserves the terminal object, the 2-cells <tex>\Phi _p</tex> and <tex>\Phi _c</tex> are invertible, and the right mate <tex>\Phi _q</tex> of <tex>\Phi _p</tex> depicted below is invertible:</p>      <center><img src="resources/03303924d34e2978dc17f302a24d0814-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><p>It is seen by drawing string diagrams that if the underlying cells of a <link href="jms-00E7.xml" type="local" title="Transformations of homomorphisms of natural models">transformation</link> of <link href="jms-00E7.xml" type="local" title="Transformations of homomorphisms of natural models">homomorphisms of natural models</link> are invertible, then the transformation itself is invertible. Furthermore, it follows from the discreteness of <tex>E</tex> and <tex>U</tex> over <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> that the transformation laws uniquely determine the components <tex>\alpha _E</tex> and <tex>\alpha _U</tex> if they exist. As such, the only data in a <link href="jms-00E7.xml" type="local" title="Transformations of homomorphisms of natural models">transformation</link> is the lowest cell <tex>\alpha _{ \mathcal {C}}</tex> acting on contexts.</p></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>14536</anchor> <rss>jms-00E4.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00E4</addr>  <route>jms-00E4.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>10</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic description of natural models</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <em>natural model</em> is described by the following structure in the bicategory of (small) categories:</p><ol>  <li>    a sequence of discrete fibrations <tex>E \xrightarrow {p} U \xrightarrow {c}  \mathcal {C}</tex> such that <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> has a terminal object:
